qTextArr: ['and what is the use of a book,', 'without pictures or conversations?']
qText: and what is the use of a book, without pictures or conversations?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Oh\ndear! Oh dear! I shall be late!']
qText:
Oh
dear! Oh dear! I shall be late!
speaker: The White Rabbit

qTextArr:
['Well!', "after such a fall as this, I shall
think nothing of tumbling down stairs! How brave they'll all think me
at home! Why, I wouldn't say anything about it, even if I fell off the
top of the house!"]
qText:
Well! after such a fall as this, I shall
think nothing of tumbling down stairs! How brave they'll all think me
at home! Why, I wouldn't say anything about it, even if I fell off the
top of the house!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["I wonder how
many miles I've fallen by this time?", 'I must be
getting somewhere near the centre of the earth. Let me see: that would
be four thousand miles down, I think--', "--yes, that's about the right distance--but
then I wonder what Latitude or Longitude I've got to?"]
qText:
I wonder how
many miles I've fallen by this time? I must be
getting somewhere near the centre of the earth. Let me see: that would
be four thousand miles down, I think-- --yes, that's about the right distance--but
then I wonder what Latitude or Longitude I've got to?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["I wonder if I shall fall right _through_
the earth! How funny it'll seem to come out among the people that walk
with their heads downward! The Antipathies, I think--", "--but I shall have to ask them what the name of the
country is, you know. Please, Ma'am, is this New Zealand or Australia?", "And what
an ignorant little girl she'll think me for asking! No, it'll never do
to ask: perhaps I shall see it written up somewhere."]
qText:
I wonder if I shall fall right _through_
the earth! How funny it'll seem to come out among the people that walk
with their heads downward! The Antipathies, I think-- --but I shall have to ask them what the name of the
country is, you know. Please, Ma'am, is this New Zealand or Australia? And what
an ignorant little girl she'll think me for asking! No, it'll never do
to ask: perhaps I shall see it written up somewhere.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["Dinah'll miss me very much to-night, I should think!", "I hope they'll remember her saucer of milk at
tea-time. Dinah my dear! I wish you were down here with me! There are
no mice in the air, I'm afraid, but you might catch a bat, and that's
very like a mouse, you know. But do cats eat bats, I wonder?", 'Do cats eat bats? Do cats eat bats?', 'Do bats eat cats?']
qText:
Dinah'll miss me very much to-night, I should think! I hope they'll remember her saucer of milk at
tea-time. Dinah my dear! I wish you were down here with me! There are
no mice in the air, I'm afraid, but you might catch a bat, and that's
very like a mouse, you know. But do cats eat bats, I wonder? Do cats eat bats? Do cats eat bats? Do bats eat cats?
speaker: Alice
refExp: Alice began to get rather sleepy and went on saying to herself

qTextArr: ['Now, Dinah, tell me the truth: did you ever eat a bat?']
qText: Now, Dinah, tell me the truth: did you ever eat a bat?
speaker: Alice
refExp: she was and to she was walking hand in hand with Dinah and saying to her

qTextArr: ["Oh my ears\nand whiskers, how late it's getting!"]
qText:
Oh my ears
and whiskers, how late it's getting!
speaker: The White Rabbit

qTextArr: ['and even if my head would go through,', 'it would be of very little use without my shoulders. Oh,\nhow I wish I could shut up like a telescope! I think I could, if I only\nknew how to begin.']
qText:
and even if my head would go through, it would be of very little use without my shoulders. Oh,
how I wish I could shut up like a telescope! I think I could, if I only
knew how to begin.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['which certainly was not here\nbefore,']
qText:
which certainly was not here
before,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["No, I'll look first,", "and see whether it's marked '_poison_' or not"]
qText: No, I'll look first, and see whether it's marked '_poison_' or not
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['What a curious feeling!', 'I must be shutting up like a\ntelescope.']
qText:
What a curious feeling! I must be shutting up like a
telescope.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['for it might end, you know,', 'in my going out altogether, like a candle. I\nwonder what I should be like then?', "Come, there's no use in crying like that!", 'I advise you to leave off this minute!']
qText:
for it might end, you know, in my going out altogether, like a candle. I
wonder what I should be like then? Come, there's no use in crying like that! I advise you to leave off this minute!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["But it's no use now,", "to pretend to be two\npeople! Why, there's hardly enough of me left to make _one_ respectable\nperson!"]
qText:
But it's no use now, to pretend to be two
people! Why, there's hardly enough of me left to make _one_ respectable
person!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Well, I'll eat it,", "and if it makes me grow larger, I can reach the key; and if it\nmakes me grow smaller, I can creep under the door; so either way I'll\nget into the garden, and I don't care which happens!"]
qText:
Well, I'll eat it, and if it makes me grow larger, I can reach the key; and if it
makes me grow smaller, I can creep under the door; so either way I'll
get into the garden, and I don't care which happens!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Which way? Which\nway?']
qText:
Which way? Which
way?
speaker: Alice
refExp: She ate a little bit and said anxiously to herself

qTextArr: ['Curiouser and curiouser!', "now I'm\nopening out like the largest telescope that ever was! Good-bye, feet!"]
qText:
Curiouser and curiouser! now I'm
opening out like the largest telescope that ever was! Good-bye, feet!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["Oh, my poor little feet, I
wonder who will put on your shoes and stockings for you now, dears? I'm
sure _I_ shan't be able! I shall be a great deal too far off to trouble
myself about you: you must manage the best way you can;--but I must be
kind to them,", "or perhaps they won't walk the way I
want to go! Let me see: I'll give them a new pair of boots every
Christmas."]
qText:
Oh, my poor little feet, I
wonder who will put on your shoes and stockings for you now, dears? I'm
sure _I_ shan't be able! I shall be a great deal too far off to trouble
myself about you: you must manage the best way you can;--but I must be
kind to them, or perhaps they won't walk the way I
want to go! Let me see: I'll give them a new pair of boots every
Christmas.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
['They must
go by the carrier,', "and how funny it'll seem, sending
presents to one's own feet! And how odd the directions will look!

     _Alice's Right Foot, Esq., Hearthrug, near the Fender,_ (_with
     Alice's love_).

Oh dear, what nonsense I'm talking!"]
qText:
They must
go by the carrier, and how funny it'll seem, sending
presents to one's own feet! And how odd the directions will look!

     _Alice's Right Foot, Esq., Hearthrug, near the Fender,_ (_with
     Alice's love_).

Oh dear, what nonsense I'm talking!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['You ought to be ashamed of yourself,', 'a great girl like\nyou,', 'to go on crying in this way! Stop\nthis moment, I tell you!']
qText:
You ought to be ashamed of yourself, a great girl like
you, to go on crying in this way! Stop
this moment, I tell you!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Oh! the Duchess, the\nDuchess! Oh! won't she be savage if I've kept her waiting!"]
qText:
Oh! the Duchess, the
Duchess! Oh! won't she be savage if I've kept her waiting!
speaker: The White Rabbit
refExp: he came trotting along in a great hurry muttering to himself

qTextArr: ['If you please,\nsir--']
qText:
If you please,
sir--
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["Dear, dear! How
queer everything is to-day! And yesterday things went on just as usual.
I wonder if I've been changed in the night? Let me think: was I the
same when I got up this morning? I almost think I can remember feeling
a little different. But if I'm not the same, the next question is, Who
in the world am I? Ah, _that's_ the great puzzle!"]
qText:
Dear, dear! How
queer everything is to-day! And yesterday things went on just as usual.
I wonder if I've been changed in the night? Let me think: was I the
same when I got up this morning? I almost think I can remember feeling
a little different. But if I'm not the same, the next question is, Who
in the world am I? Ah, _that's_ the great puzzle!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["I'm sure I'm not Ada,", "for her hair goes in such long
ringlets, and mine doesn't go in ringlets at all; and I'm sure I can't
be Mabel, for I know all sorts of things, and she, oh! she knows such a
very little! Besides, _she's_ she, and _I'm_ I, and--oh dear, how
puzzling it all is! I'll try if I know all the things I used to know.
Let me see: four times five is twelve, and four times six is thirteen,
and four times seven is--oh dear! I shall never get to twenty at that
rate! However, the Multiplication Table doesn't signify: let's try
Geography. London is the capital of Paris, and Paris is the capital of
Rome, and Rome--no, _that's_ all wrong, I'm certain! I must have been
changed for Mabel! I'll try and say '_How doth the little_--'"]
qText:
I'm sure I'm not Ada, for her hair goes in such long
ringlets, and mine doesn't go in ringlets at all; and I'm sure I can't
be Mabel, for I know all sorts of things, and she, oh! she knows such a
very little! Besides, _she's_ she, and _I'm_ I, and--oh dear, how
puzzling it all is! I'll try if I know all the things I used to know.
Let me see: four times five is twelve, and four times six is thirteen,
and four times seven is--oh dear! I shall never get to twenty at that
rate! However, the Multiplication Table doesn't signify: let's try
Geography. London is the capital of Paris, and Paris is the capital of
Rome, and Rome--no, _that's_ all wrong, I'm certain! I must have been
changed for Mabel! I'll try and say '_How doth the little_--'
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["I'm sure those are not the right words,", "I must be Mabel after all, and
I shall have to go and live in that poky little house, and have next to
no toys to play with, and oh! ever so many lessons to learn! No, I've
made up my mind about it; if I'm Mabel, I'll stay down here! It'll be
no use their putting their heads down and saying 'Come up again, dear!'
I shall only look up and say 'Who am I then? Tell me that first, and
then, if I like being that person, I'll come up: if not, I'll stay down
here till I'm somebody else'--but, oh dear!", 'I do wish they _would_ put their heads down! I am so
_very_ tired of being all alone here!']
qText:
I'm sure those are not the right words, I must be Mabel after all, and
I shall have to go and live in that poky little house, and have next to
no toys to play with, and oh! ever so many lessons to learn! No, I've
made up my mind about it; if I'm Mabel, I'll stay down here! It'll be
no use their putting their heads down and saying 'Come up again, dear!'
I shall only look up and say 'Who am I then? Tell me that first, and
then, if I like being that person, I'll come up: if not, I'll stay down
here till I'm somebody else'--but, oh dear! I do wish they _would_ put their heads down! I am so
_very_ tired of being all alone here!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['How _can_ I have done that?', 'I must be\ngrowing small again.']
qText:
How _can_ I have done that? I must be
growing small again.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['That _was_ a narrow escape!', 'and\nnow for the garden!']
qText:
That _was_ a narrow escape! and
now for the garden!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['and things are worse than\never,', "for I never was so small as this\nbefore, never! And I declare it's too bad, that it is!"]
qText:
and things are worse than
ever, for I never was so small as this
before, never! And I declare it's too bad, that it is!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['and in that case I can go back by\nrailway,']
qText:
and in that case I can go back by
railway,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["I wish I hadn't cried so much!", 'I shall be punished for it now, I suppose, by\nbeing drowned in my own tears! That _will_ be a queer thing, to be\nsure! However, everything is queer to-day.']
qText:
I wish I hadn't cried so much! I shall be punished for it now, I suppose, by
being drowned in my own tears! That _will_ be a queer thing, to be
sure! However, everything is queer to-day.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Would it be of any use, now,', "to speak to this mouse?\nEverything is so out-of-the-way down here, that I should think very\nlikely it can talk: at any rate, there's no harm in trying."]
qText:
Would it be of any use, now, to speak to this mouse?
Everything is so out-of-the-way down here, that I should think very
likely it can talk: at any rate, there's no harm in trying.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['O Mouse, do you know the way out of this pool? I am very tired\nof swimming about here, O Mouse!']
qText:
O Mouse, do you know the way out of this pool? I am very tired
of swimming about here, O Mouse!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Perhaps it doesn't understand English,", "I daresay it's\na French mouse, come over with William the Conqueror."]
qText:
Perhaps it doesn't understand English, I daresay it's
a French mouse, come over with William the Conqueror.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['O? est ma chatte?']
qText: O? est ma chatte?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Oh, I beg your pardon!', "I quite forgot you didn't like\ncats."]
qText:
Oh, I beg your pardon! I quite forgot you didn't like
cats.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Not like cats!', 'Would\n_you_ like cats if you were me?']
qText:
Not like cats! Would
_you_ like cats if you were me?
speaker: The Mouse

qTextArr:
['Well, perhaps not,', "don't be angry
about it. And yet I wish I could show you our cat Dinah: I think you'd
take a fancy to cats if you could only see her. She is such a dear
quiet thing,", "and she sits purring so nicely by the fire, licking her
paws and washing her face--and she is such a nice soft thing to
nurse--and she's such a capital one for catching mice--oh, I beg your
pardon!", "We won't talk
about her any more if you'd rather not."]
qText:
Well, perhaps not, don't be angry
about it. And yet I wish I could show you our cat Dinah: I think you'd
take a fancy to cats if you could only see her. She is such a dear
quiet thing, and she sits purring so nicely by the fire, licking her
paws and washing her face--and she is such a nice soft thing to
nurse--and she's such a capital one for catching mice--oh, I beg your
pardon! We won't talk
about her any more if you'd rather not.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['We indeed!', "As if _I_ would talk on such a subject! Our family always\n_hated_ cats: nasty, low, vulgar things! Don't let me hear the name\nagain!"]
qText:
We indeed! As if _I_ would talk on such a subject! Our family always
_hated_ cats: nasty, low, vulgar things! Don't let me hear the name
again!
speaker: The Mouse

qTextArr: ["I won't indeed!", 'Are you--are you fond--of--of dogs?']
qText: I won't indeed! Are you--are you fond--of--of dogs?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["There is such a nice little dog near
our house I should like to show you! A little bright-eyed terrier, you
know, with oh, such long curly brown hair! And it'll fetch things when
you throw them, and it'll sit up and beg for its dinner, and all sorts
of things--I can't remember half of them--and it belongs to a farmer, you
know, and he says it's so useful, it's worth a hundred pounds! He says
it kills all the rats and--oh dear!", "I'm afraid I've offended it again!"]
qText:

qText:
I wish I hadn't mentioned Dinah! Nobody seems to like her, down here, and I'm sure she's the best
cat in the world! Oh, my dear Dinah! I wonder if I shall ever see you
any more!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["The Duchess! The Duchess! Oh my dear paws! Oh\nmy fur and whiskers! She'll get me executed, as sure as ferrets are\nferrets! Where _can_ I have dropped them, I wonder?"]
qText:
The Duchess! The Duchess! Oh my dear paws! Oh
my fur and whiskers! She'll get me executed, as sure as ferrets are
ferrets! Where _can_ I have dropped them, I wonder?

qText:
Why, Mary Ann, what _are_ you
doing out here? Run home this moment, and fetch me a pair of gloves and
a fan! Quick, now!
speaker: The White Rabbit
refExp: the Rabbit noticed Alice as she went hunting about and called out to her

qTextArr: ['He took me for his housemaid,', "How\nsurprised he'll be when he finds out who I am! But I'd better take him\nhis fan and gloves--that is, if I can find them."]
qText:
He took me for his housemaid, How
surprised he'll be when he finds out who I am! But I'd better take him
his fan and gloves--that is, if I can find them.
speaker: Alice
menEnts: [[['The White Rabbit'], ['The White Rabbit']], [['The White Rabbit'], ['The White Rabbit'], ['The Rabbit']]]

qTextArr:
['How queer it seems,', "to be going messages for
a rabbit! I suppose Dinah'll be sending me on messages next!", "'Miss Alice! Come
here directly, and get ready for your walk!' 'Coming in a minute,
nurse! But I've got to see that the mouse doesn't get out.' Only I
don't think,", "that they'd let Dinah stop in the house
if it began ordering people about like that!"]
qText:
How queer it seems, to be going messages for
a rabbit! I suppose Dinah'll be sending me on messages next! 'Miss Alice! Come
here directly, and get ready for your walk!' 'Coming in a minute,
nurse! But I've got to see that the mouse doesn't get out.' Only I
don't think, that they'd let Dinah stop in the house
if it began ordering people about like that!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
['I know _something_ interesting is sure to
happen,', "whenever I eat or drink anything; so
I'll just see what this bottle does. I do hope it'll make me grow large
again, for really I'm quite tired of being such a tiny little thing!"]
qText:
I know _something_ interesting is sure to
happen, whenever I eat or drink anything; so
I'll just see what this bottle does. I do hope it'll make me grow large
again, for really I'm quite tired of being such a tiny little thing!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["That's quite enough--I hope I shan't\ngrow any more--As it is, I can't get out at the door--I do wish I hadn't\ndrunk quite so much!"]
qText:
That's quite enough--I hope I shan't
grow any more--As it is, I can't get out at the door--I do wish I hadn't
drunk quite so much!
speaker: Alice
refExp: She hastily put down the bottle saying to herself

qTextArr: ['Now I\ncan do no more, whatever happens. What _will_ become of me?']
qText:
Now I
can do no more, whatever happens. What _will_ become of me?
speaker: Alice
refExp: she put one arm out of the window and one foot up the chimney and said to herself

qTextArr:
['It was much pleasanter at home,', "when one wasn't
always growing larger and smaller, and being ordered about by mice and
rabbits. I almost wish I hadn't gone down that rabbit-hole--and yet--and
yet--it's rather curious, you know, this sort of life! I do wonder what
_can_ have happened to me! When I used to read fairy-tales, I fancied
that kind of thing never happened, and now here I am in the middle of
one! There ought to be a book written about me, that there ought! And
when I grow up, I'll write one--but I'm grown up now,", "at least there's no room to grow up any more _here_."]
qText:
It was much pleasanter at home, when one wasn't
always growing larger and smaller, and being ordered about by mice and
rabbits. I almost wish I hadn't gone down that rabbit-hole--and yet--and
yet--it's rather curious, you know, this sort of life! I do wonder what
_can_ have happened to me! When I used to read fairy-tales, I fancied
that kind of thing never happened, and now here I am in the middle of
one! There ought to be a book written about me, that there ought! And
when I grow up, I'll write one--but I'm grown up now, at least there's no room to grow up any more _here_.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['But then,', "shall I _never_ get any older than I am\nnow? That'll be a comfort, one way--never to be an old woman--but\nthen--always to have lessons to learn! Oh, I shouldn't like _that!_"]
qText:
But then, shall I _never_ get any older than I am
now? That'll be a comfort, one way--never to be an old woman--but
then--always to have lessons to learn! Oh, I shouldn't like _that!_
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Oh, you foolish Alice!', "How can you learn\nlessons in here? Why, there's hardly room for _you_, and no room at all\nfor any lesson-books!"]
qText:
Oh, you foolish Alice! How can you learn
lessons in here? Why, there's hardly room for _you_, and no room at all
for any lesson-books!
speaker: Alice

Digging for apples, indeed! Here! Come and

qText: Well, it's got no business there, at any rate: go and take it away!

Sure, I don't like it, yer honour, at all, at

qText: Do as I tell you, you coward!

qTextArr:
['What a number
of cucumber-frames there must be!', "I wonder what
they'll do next! As for pulling me out of the window, I only wish they
_could!_ I'm sure _I_ don't want to stay in here any longer!"]
qText:
What a number
of cucumber-frames there must be! I wonder what
they'll do next! As for pulling me out of the window, I only wish they
_could!_ I'm sure _I_ don't want to stay in here any longer!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Oh! So Bill's got to come down the chimney, has he?", "Shy, they seem to put everything upon Bill! I wouldn't be in\nBill's place for a good deal: this fireplace is narrow, to be sure; but\nI _think_ I can kick a little!"]
qText:
Oh! So Bill's got to come down the chimney, has he? Shy, they seem to put everything upon Bill! I wouldn't be in
Bill's place for a good deal: this fireplace is narrow, to be sure; but
I _think_ I can kick a little!
speaker: Alice

qText: This is Bill,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Catch him, you by the hedge!']
qText: Catch him, you by the hedge!
speaker: The White Rabbit

qTextArr: ["That's Bill,"]
qText: That's Bill,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Well, I hardly know--No more, thank ye; I'm better now--but I'm\na deal too flustered to tell you--all I know is, something comes at me\nlike a Jack-in-the-box, and up I goes like a sky-rocket!"]
qText:
Well, I hardly know--No more, thank ye; I'm better now--but I'm
a deal too flustered to tell you--all I know is, something comes at me
like a Jack-in-the-box, and up I goes like a sky-rocket!

qText: We must burn the house down!

qTextArr: ["If you do, I'll set Dinah at you!"]
qText: If you do, I'll set Dinah at you!
speaker: Alice

I
wonder what they _will_ do next! If they had any sense, they'd take the

I'll put a stop to

You'd better not do that

qTextArr: ['If I eat one of these cakes,', "it's sure to make\n_some_ change in my size; and as it can't possibly make me larger, it\nmust make me smaller, I suppose."]
qText:
If I eat one of these cakes, it's sure to make
_some_ change in my size; and as it can't possibly make me larger, it
must make me smaller, I suppose.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["The first thing I've got to do,", 'is to grow to my right size again; and the\nsecond thing is to find my way into that lovely garden. I think that\nwill be the best plan.']
qText:
The first thing I've got to do, is to grow to my right size again; and the
second thing is to find my way into that lovely garden. I think that
will be the best plan.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Poor little\nthing!']
qText:
Poor little
thing!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
['And yet what a dear little puppy it was!', "I should have liked teaching it tricks very much, if--if I'd
only been the right size to do it! Oh dear! I'd nearly forgotten that
I've got to grow up again! Let me see--how _is_ it to be managed? I
suppose I ought to eat or drink something or other; but the great
question is, what?"]
qText:
And yet what a dear little puppy it was! I should have liked teaching it tricks very much, if--if I'd
only been the right size to do it! Oh dear! I'd nearly forgotten that
I've got to grow up again! Let me see--how _is_ it to be managed? I
suppose I ought to eat or drink something or other; but the great
question is, what?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Who are _you?_']
qText: Who are _you?_
speaker: The Caterpillar

qTextArr: ['I--I hardly know, sir, just at present--at least I know\nwho I _was_ when I got up this morning, but I think I must have been\nchanged several times since then.']
qText:
I--I hardly know, sir, just at present--at least I know
who I _was_ when I got up this morning, but I think I must have been
changed several times since then.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['What do you mean by that?', 'Explain\nyourself!']
qText:
What do you mean by that? Explain
yourself!
speaker: The Caterpillar

qTextArr: ["I can't explain _myself_, I'm afraid, sir,", "because I'm\nnot myself, you see."]
qText:
I can't explain _myself_, I'm afraid, sir, because I'm
not myself, you see.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["I don't see,"]
qText: I don't see,
speaker: The Caterpillar

qTextArr: ["I'm afraid I can't put it more clearly,", "for I can't understand it myself to begin with; and being so many\ndifferent sizes in a day is very confusing."]
qText:
I'm afraid I can't put it more clearly, for I can't understand it myself to begin with; and being so many
different sizes in a day is very confusing.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["It isn't,"]
qText: It isn't,

qTextArr:
["Well, perhaps you haven't found it so yet,", "but when you
have to turn into a chrysalis--you will some day, you know--and then
after that into a butterfly, I should think you'll feel it a little
queer, won't you?"]
qText:
Well, perhaps you haven't found it so yet, but when you
have to turn into a chrysalis--you will some day, you know--and then

queer, won't you?

qTextArr: ['Not a bit,']
qText: Not a bit,

Well, perhaps your feelings may be different, all I know

I

So you

Well, I've tried to say but it all

Not _quite_ right, I'm afraid, some of the

qTextArr: ['One side will make you grow taller, and the other side will make you\ngrow shorter.']
qText:
One side will make you grow taller, and the other side will make you
grow shorter.
speaker: The Caterpillar
refExp: it got down off the mushroom and crawled away in the grass merely remarking

qTextArr: ['One side of _what?_ The other side of _what?_']
qText: One side of _what?_ The other side of _what?_
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Of the mushroom,']
qText: Of the mushroom,
speaker: The Caterpillar

qTextArr: ['And now which is which?']
qText: And now which is which?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Come, my head's free at last!", 'What _can_ all that green stuff be?', "And where _have_ my\nshoulders got to? And oh, my poor hands, how is it I can't see you?"]
qText:
Come, my head's free at last! What _can_ all that green stuff be? And where _have_ my
shoulders got to? And oh, my poor hands, how is it I can't see you?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Serpent!']
qText: Serpent!
speaker: The Pigeon

qTextArr: ["I'm _not_ a serpent!", 'Let me alone!']
qText: I'm _not_ a serpent! Let me alone!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Serpent, I say again!', "I've tried every way, and nothing\nseems to suit them!"]
qText:
Serpent, I say again! I've tried every way, and nothing
seems to suit them!
speaker: The Pigeon

qTextArr: ["I haven't the least idea what you're talking about,"]
qText: I haven't the least idea what you're talking about,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["I've tried the roots of trees, and I've tried banks, and I've tried\nhedges,", "but those\nserpents! There's no pleasing them!"]
qText:
I've tried the roots of trees, and I've tried banks, and I've tried
hedges, but those
serpents! There's no pleasing them!
speaker: The Pigeon

qTextArr: ["As if it wasn't trouble enough hatching the eggs,", "but I must be on the look-out for serpents night and day! Why, I\nhaven't had a wink of sleep these three weeks!"]
qText:
As if it wasn't trouble enough hatching the eggs, but I must be on the look-out for serpents night and day! Why, I
haven't had a wink of sleep these three weeks!
speaker: The Pigeon

qTextArr: ["I'm very sorry you've been annoyed,"]
qText: I'm very sorry you've been annoyed,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["And just as I'd taken the highest tree in the wood,", 'and just as I was thinking I\nshould be free of them at last, they must needs come wriggling down\nfrom the sky! Ugh, Serpent!']
qText:
And just as I'd taken the highest tree in the wood, and just as I was thinking I
should be free of them at last, they must needs come wriggling down
from the sky! Ugh, Serpent!
speaker: The Pigeon

qTextArr: ["But I'm _not_ a serpent, I tell you!", "I'm a--I'm a--"]
qText: But I'm _not_ a serpent, I tell you! I'm a--I'm a--
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Well! _What_ are you?', "I can see you're trying to\ninvent something!"]
qText:
Well! _What_ are you? I can see you're trying to
invent something!
speaker: The Pigeon

qTextArr: ["I--I'm a little girl,"]
qText: I--I'm a little girl,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
['A likely story indeed!', "I've seen a good many little girls in my time, but never
_one_ with such a neck as that! No, no! You're a serpent; and there's
no use denying it. I suppose you'll be telling me next that you never
tasted an egg!"]
qText:
A likely story indeed! I've seen a good many little girls in my time, but never
_one_ with such a neck as that! No, no! You're a serpent; and there's
no use denying it. I suppose you'll be telling me next that you never
tasted an egg!
speaker: The Pigeon

qTextArr: ['I _have_ tasted eggs, certainly,', 'but little girls eat eggs quite as much as serpents do, you\nknow.']
qText:
I _have_ tasted eggs, certainly, but little girls eat eggs quite as much as serpents do, you
know.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["I don't believe it,", "but if they do, why then\nthey're a kind of serpent, that's all I can say."]
qText:
I don't believe it, but if they do, why then
they're a kind of serpent, that's all I can say.
speaker: The Pigeon

qTextArr: ["You're\nlooking for eggs, I know _that_ well enough; and what does it matter to\nme whether you're a little girl or a serpent?"]
qText:
You're
looking for eggs, I know _that_ well enough; and what does it matter to
me whether you're a little girl or a serpent?
speaker: The Pigeon
refExp: the Pigeon the opportunity of adding

qTextArr: ['It matters a good deal to _me_,', "but I'm not\nlooking for eggs, as it happens; and if I was, I shouldn't want\n_yours_: I don't like them raw."]
qText:
It matters a good deal to _me_, but I'm not
looking for eggs, as it happens; and if I was, I shouldn't want
_yours_: I don't like them raw.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Well, be off, then!']
qText: Well, be off, then!
speaker: The Pigeon

qTextArr:
["Come, there's half my plan
done now! How puzzling all these changes are! I'm never sure what I'm
going to be, from one minute to another! However, I've got back to my
right size: the next thing is, to get into that beautiful garden--how
_is_ that to be done, I wonder?"]
qText:
Come, there's half my plan
done now! How puzzling all these changes are! I'm never sure what I'm
going to be, from one minute to another! However, I've got back to my
right size: the next thing is, to get into that beautiful garden--how
_is_ that to be done, I wonder?
speaker: Alice
refExp: got used to it in a few minutes and began talking to herself

qTextArr: ['Whoever lives there,', "it'll never do to come upon them\n_this_ size: why, I should frighten them out of their wits!"]
qText:
Whoever lives there, it'll never do to come upon them
_this_ size: why, I should frighten them out of their wits!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['For the Duchess. An invitation from the\nQueen to play croquet.']
qText:
For the Duchess. An invitation from the
Queen to play croquet.
speaker: The Fish-Footman
refExp: he handed over to the other saying

qTextArr: ['From the Queen.\nAn invitation for the Duchess to play croquet.']
qText:
From the Queen.
An invitation for the Duchess to play croquet.
speaker: The Frog-Footman

qTextArr:
["There's no sort of use in knocking,", "and that for
two reasons. First, because I'm on the same side of the door as you
are; secondly, because they're making such a noise inside, no one could
possibly hear you."]
qText:
There's no sort of use in knocking, and that for
two reasons. First, because I'm on the same side of the door as you
are; secondly, because they're making such a noise inside, no one could
possibly hear you.
speaker: The Frog-Footman

qTextArr: ['Please, then,', 'how am I to get in?']
qText: Please, then, how am I to get in?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['There might be some sense in your knocking,', 'if we had the door between us. For instance,\nif you were _inside_, you might knock, and I could let you out, you\nknow.']
qText:
There might be some sense in your knocking, if we had the door between us. For instance,
if you were _inside_, you might knock, and I could let you out, you
know.
speaker: The Frog-Footman

qTextArr: ["But perhaps he can't help it,", 'his eyes are so _very_ nearly at the top of his\nhead. But at any rate he might answer questions.']
qText:
But perhaps he can't help it, his eyes are so _very_ nearly at the top of his
head. But at any rate he might answer questions.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['How am I to get in?']
qText: How am I to get in?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['I shall sit here,', 'till tomorrow--']
qText: I shall sit here, till tomorrow--
speaker: The Frog-Footman

qTextArr: ['--or next day, maybe,']
qText: --or next day, maybe,
speaker: The Frog-Footman

qTextArr: ['How am I to get in?']
qText: How am I to get in?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['_Are_ you to get in at all?', "That's the first\nquestion, you know."]
qText:
_Are_ you to get in at all? That's the first
question, you know.
speaker: The Frog-Footman

qTextArr: ["It's really\ndreadful,", "the way all the creatures argue.\nIt's enough to drive one crazy!"]
qText:
It's really
dreadful, the way all the creatures argue.
It's enough to drive one crazy!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['I shall sit here,', 'on and off, for\ndays and days.']
qText:
I shall sit here, on and off, for
days and days.
speaker: The Frog-Footman

qTextArr: ['But what am _I_ to do?']
qText: But what am _I_ to do?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Anything you like,']
qText: Anything you like,
speaker: The Frog-Footman

qTextArr: ["Oh, there's no use in talking to him,", "he's\nperfectly idiotic!"]
qText:
Oh, there's no use in talking to him, he's
perfectly idiotic!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["There's certainly too much pepper in that soup!"]
qText: There's certainly too much pepper in that soup!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Please would you tell me,', 'why\nyour cat grins like that?']
qText:
Please would you tell me, why
your cat grins like that?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["It's a Cheshire cat,", "and that's why. Pig!"]
qText: It's a Cheshire cat, and that's why. Pig!
speaker: The Duchess

qTextArr: ["I didn't know that Cheshire cats always grinned; in fact, I didn't\nknow that cats _could_ grin."]
qText:
I didn't know that Cheshire cats always grinned; in fact, I didn't
know that cats _could_ grin.
speaker: Alice
refExp: she took courage and went on

qTextArr: ['They all can,', "and most of 'em do."]
qText: They all can, and most of 'em do.
speaker: The Duchess

qTextArr: ["I don't know of any that do,"]
qText: I don't know of any that do,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["You don't know much,", "and that's a fact."]
qText: You don't know much, and that's a fact.
speaker: The Duchess

qTextArr: ["Oh, _please_ mind what you're doing!", 'Oh, there goes his _precious_ nose!']
qText: Oh, _please_ mind what you're doing! Oh, there goes his _precious_ nose!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['If everybody minded their own business,', 'the world would go round a deal faster than it does.']
qText: If everybody minded their own business, the world would go round a deal faster than it does.
speaker: The Duchess

qTextArr: ['Which would _not_ be an advantage,', 'Just\nthink of what work it would make with the day and night! You see the\nearth takes twenty-four hours to turn round on its axis--']
qText:
Which would _not_ be an advantage, Just
think of what work it would make with the day and night! You see the
earth takes twenty-four hours to turn round on its axis--
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Talking of axes,', 'chop off her head!']
qText: Talking of axes, chop off her head!
speaker: The Duchess

qTextArr: ['Twenty-four hours, I _think_; or\nis it twelve? I--']
qText:
Twenty-four hours, I _think_; or
is it twelve? I--
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Oh, don't bother _me_,", 'I never could abide\nfigures!']
qText:
Oh, don't bother _me_, I never could abide
figures!
speaker: The Duchess

qTextArr:
['"Speak roughly to your little boy,
    And beat him when he sneezes:
He only does it to annoy,
    Because he knows it teases."']
qText:
"Speak roughly to your little boy,
    And beat him when he sneezes:
He only does it to annoy,
    Because he knows it teases."
speaker: The Duchess
refExp: she began nursing her child again singing a sort of lullaby to it

qTextArr:
['"I speak severely to my boy,
    I beat him when he sneezes;
For he can thoroughly enjoy
    The pepper when he pleases!"']
qText:
"I speak severely to my boy,
    I beat him when he sneezes;
For he can thoroughly enjoy
    The pepper when he pleases!"
speaker: The Duchess

qTextArr: ['Here! you may nurse it a bit, if you like!', 'I must go and get ready to play\ncroquet with the Queen,']
qText:
Here! you may nurse it a bit, if you like! I must go and get ready to play
croquet with the Queen,
speaker: The Duchess

qTextArr: ['just like a star-fish,', "If I don't take this child away with me,"]
qText: just like a star-fish, If I don't take this child away with me,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["they're sure to kill it in a day or two: wouldn't it be\nmurder to leave it behind?"]
qText:
they're sure to kill it in a day or two: wouldn't it be
murder to leave it behind?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Don't grunt,", "that's not at all a proper way of\nexpressing yourself."]
qText:
Don't grunt, that's not at all a proper way of
expressing yourself.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['But perhaps it was only\nsobbing,']
qText:
But perhaps it was only
sobbing,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["If you're going to turn into a pig, my dear,", "I'll have nothing more to do with you. Mind\nnow!"]
qText:
If you're going to turn into a pig, my dear, I'll have nothing more to do with you. Mind
now!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Now, what am I to do\nwith this creature when I get it home?']
qText:
Now, what am I to do
with this creature when I get it home?
speaker: Alice
refExp: Alice was just beginning to think to herself

qTextArr: ['If it had grown up,', 'it would have made a dreadfully ugly child: but it makes\nrather a handsome pig, I think.']
qText:
If it had grown up, it would have made a dreadfully ugly child: but it makes
rather a handsome pig, I think.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['if one only knew the right way to change them--']
qText: if one only knew the right way to change them--
speaker: Alice
refExp: she began thinking over other children she knew who might do very well as pigs and was just saying to herself

qTextArr: ['Cheshire Puss,']
qText: Cheshire Puss,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Come, it's pleased so far,"]
qText: Come, it's pleased so far,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Would you tell me, please, which way I ought to go from here?']
qText: Would you tell me, please, which way I ought to go from here?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['That depends a good deal on where you want to get to,']
qText: That depends a good deal on where you want to get to,
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ["I don't much care where--"]
qText: I don't much care where--
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Then it doesn't matter which way you go,"]
qText: Then it doesn't matter which way you go,
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ['--so long as I get _somewhere_,']
qText: --so long as I get _somewhere_,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Oh, you're sure to do that,", 'if you only walk long\nenough.']
qText:
Oh, you're sure to do that, if you only walk long
enough.
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ['What sort of people live about here?']
qText: What sort of people live about here?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['In _that_ direction,', 'lives\na Hatter: and in _that_ direction,', "lives a\nMarch Hare. Visit either you like: they're both mad."]
qText:
In _that_ direction, lives
a Hatter: and in _that_ direction, lives a
March Hare. Visit either you like: they're both mad.
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ["But I don't want to go among mad people,"]
qText: But I don't want to go among mad people,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Oh, you can't help that,", "we're all mad here. I'm mad.\nYou're mad."]
qText:
Oh, you can't help that, we're all mad here. I'm mad.
You're mad.
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ["How do you know I'm mad?"]
qText: How do you know I'm mad?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['You must be,', "or you wouldn't have come here."]
qText: You must be, or you wouldn't have come here.
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ["And how\ndo you know that you're mad?"]
qText:
And how
do you know that you're mad?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['To begin with,', "a dog's not mad. You grant that?"]
qText: To begin with, a dog's not mad. You grant that?
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ['I suppose so,']
qText: I suppose so,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Well, then,', "you see, a dog growls when it's angry,\nand wags its tail when it's pleased. Now _I_ growl when I'm pleased,\nand wag my tail when I'm angry. Therefore I'm mad."]
qText:
Well, then, you see, a dog growls when it's angry,
and wags its tail when it's pleased. Now _I_ growl when I'm pleased,
and wag my tail when I'm angry. Therefore I'm mad.
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ['_I_ call it purring, not growling,']
qText: _I_ call it purring, not growling,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Call it what you like,', 'Do you play croquet with the\nQueen to-day?']
qText:
Call it what you like, Do you play croquet with the
Queen to-day?
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ['I should like it very much,', "but I haven't been invited\nyet."]
qText:
I should like it very much, but I haven't been invited
yet.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["You'll see me there,", 'By-the-bye, what became of the baby?', "I'd nearly\nforgotten to ask."]
qText:
You'll see me there, By-the-bye, what became of the baby? I'd nearly
forgotten to ask.
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ['It turned into a pig,']
qText: It turned into a pig,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['I thought it would,']
qText: I thought it would,
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ["I've seen hatters before,", "the March Hare will be much the most interesting, and\nperhaps as this is May it won't be raving mad--at least not so mad as it\nwas in March."]
qText:
I've seen hatters before, the March Hare will be much the most interesting, and
perhaps as this is May it won't be raving mad--at least not so mad as it
was in March.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Did you say pig, or fig?']
qText: Did you say pig, or fig?
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ['I said pig,', "and I wish you wouldn't keep appearing\nand vanishing so suddenly: you make one quite giddy."]
qText:
I said pig, and I wish you wouldn't keep appearing
and vanishing so suddenly: you make one quite giddy.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['All right,']
qText: All right,
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ["Well! I've often seen a cat without a grin,", "but a\ngrin without a cat! It's the most curious thing I ever saw in my life!"]
qText:
Well! I've often seen a cat without a grin, but a
grin without a cat! It's the most curious thing I ever saw in my life!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Suppose it should be raving mad after all!\nI almost wish I'd gone to see the Hatter instead!"]
qText:
Suppose it should be raving mad after all!
I almost wish I'd gone to see the Hatter instead!
speaker: Alice
refExp: she walked up towards it rather timidly saying to herself

qTextArr: ['Very\nuncomfortable for the Dormouse,', "only, as it's asleep,\nI suppose it doesn't mind."]
qText:
Very
uncomfortable for the Dormouse, only, as it's asleep,
I suppose it doesn't mind.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["There's _plenty_ of room!"]
qText: There's _plenty_ of room!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Have some wine,']
qText: Have some wine,
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ["I don't see any wine,"]
qText: I don't see any wine,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["There isn't any,"]
qText: There isn't any,
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ["Then it wasn't very civil of you to offer it,"]
qText: Then it wasn't very civil of you to offer it,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["It wasn't very civil of you to sit down without being invited,"]
qText: It wasn't very civil of you to sit down without being invited,
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ["I didn't know it was _your_ table,", "it's laid for a great\nmany more than three."]
qText:
I didn't know it was _your_ table, it's laid for a great
many more than three.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Your hair wants cutting,']
qText: Your hair wants cutting,
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['You should learn not to make personal remarks,', "it's very rude."]
qText: You should learn not to make personal remarks, it's very rude.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Why is a raven like a writing-desk?']
qText: Why is a raven like a writing-desk?
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Come, we shall have some fun now!', "I'm glad they've\nbegun asking riddles."]
qText:
Come, we shall have some fun now! I'm glad they've
begun asking riddles.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['--I believe I can guess that']
qText: --I believe I can guess that
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Do you mean that you think you can find out the answer to it?']
qText: Do you mean that you think you can find out the answer to it?
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ['Exactly so,']
qText: Exactly so,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Then you should say what you mean,']
qText: Then you should say what you mean,
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ['I do,', "at least--at least I mean what I\nsay--that's the same thing, you know."]
qText:
I do, at least--at least I mean what I
say--that's the same thing, you know.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Not the same thing a bit!', "You might just as well\nsay that 'I see what I eat' is the same thing as 'I eat what I see'!"]
qText:
Not the same thing a bit! You might just as well
say that 'I see what I eat' is the same thing as 'I eat what I see'!
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['You might just as well say,', "that 'I like what\nI get' is the same thing as 'I get what I like'!"]
qText:
You might just as well say, that 'I like what
I get' is the same thing as 'I get what I like'!
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ['You might just as well say,', "that 'I breathe when I sleep' is the same thing\nas 'I sleep when I breathe'!"]
qText:
You might just as well say, that 'I breathe when I sleep' is the same thing
as 'I sleep when I breathe'!
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['It _is_ the same thing with you,']
qText: It _is_ the same thing with you,
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['What day of the month\nis it?']
qText:
What day of the month
is it?
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['The fourth.']
qText: The fourth.
speaker: Alice
refExp: Alice considered a little and then said

qTextArr: ['Two days wrong!', "I told you butter wouldn't suit\nthe works!"]
qText:
Two days wrong! I told you butter wouldn't suit
the works!
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['It was the _best_ butter,']
qText: It was the _best_ butter,
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ['Yes, but some crumbs must have got in as well,', "you shouldn't have put it in with the bread-knife."]
qText: Yes, but some crumbs must have got in as well, you shouldn't have put it in with the bread-knife.
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['It was the _best_ butter,\nyou know.']
qText:
It was the _best_ butter,
you know.
speaker: Hare
refExp: he could think of nothing better to say

qTextArr: ['What a\nfunny watch!', "It tells the day of the month, and doesn't\ntell what o'clock it is!"]
qText:
What a
funny watch! It tells the day of the month, and doesn't
tell what o'clock it is!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Why should it?', 'Does _your_ watch tell you what\nyear it is?']
qText:
Why should it? Does _your_ watch tell you what
year it is?
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Of course not,', "but that's because it\nstays the same year for such a long time together."]
qText:
Of course not, but that's because it
stays the same year for such a long time together.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Which is just the case with _mine_,']
qText: Which is just the case with _mine_,
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ["I don't quite\nunderstand you,"]
qText:
I don't quite
understand you,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['The Dormouse is asleep again,']
qText: The Dormouse is asleep again,
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Of course, of course; just what I was going to remark myself.']
qText: Of course, of course; just what I was going to remark myself.
speaker: The Dormouse
refExp: The Dormouse shook its head impatiently and said

qTextArr: ['Have you guessed the riddle yet?']
qText: Have you guessed the riddle yet?
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['No, I give it up,', "what's the answer?"]
qText: No, I give it up, what's the answer?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["I haven't the slightest idea,"]
qText: I haven't the slightest idea,
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Nor I,']
qText: Nor I,
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ['I think you might do something better with the\ntime,', 'than waste it in asking riddles that have no\nanswers.']
qText:
I think you might do something better with the
time, than waste it in asking riddles that have no
answers.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['If you knew Time as well as I do,', "you wouldn't talk\nabout wasting _it_. It's _him_."]
qText:
If you knew Time as well as I do, you wouldn't talk
about wasting _it_. It's _him_.
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ["I don't know what you mean,"]
qText: I don't know what you mean,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Of course you don't!", 'I dare say you never even spoke to Time!']
qText: Of course you don't! I dare say you never even spoke to Time!
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Perhaps not,', 'but I know I have to beat\ntime when I learn music.']
qText:
Perhaps not, but I know I have to beat
time when I learn music.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
['Ah! that accounts for it,', "He won't stand beating.
Now, if you only kept on good terms with him, he'd do almost anything
you liked with the clock. For instance, suppose it were nine o'clock in
the morning, just time to begin lessons: you'd only have to whisper a
hint to Time, and round goes the clock in a twinkling! Half-past one,
time for dinner!"]
qText:
Ah! that accounts for it, He won't stand beating.
Now, if you only kept on good terms with him, he'd do almost anything
you liked with the clock. For instance, suppose it were nine o'clock in
the morning, just time to begin lessons: you'd only have to whisper a
hint to Time, and round goes the clock in a twinkling! Half-past one,
time for dinner!
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['I only wish it was,']
qText: I only wish it was,
speaker: Hare
refExp: the March Hare said to itself

qTextArr: ['That would be grand, certainly,', "but then--I\nshouldn't be hungry for it, you know."]
qText:
That would be grand, certainly, but then--I
shouldn't be hungry for it, you know.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Not at first, perhaps,', 'but you could keep it to\nhalf-past one as long as you liked.']
qText:
Not at first, perhaps, but you could keep it to
half-past one as long as you liked.
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Is that the way _you_ manage?']
qText: Is that the way _you_ manage?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Not I!', 'We\nquarrelled last March--just before _he_ went mad, you know--', '--it was at the great concert\ngiven by the Queen of Hearts, and I had to sing', 'You know the song, perhaps?']
qText:
Not I! We
quarrelled last March--just before _he_ went mad, you know-- --it was at the great concert
given by the Queen of Hearts, and I had to sing You know the song, perhaps?
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ["I've heard something like it,"]
qText: I've heard something like it,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['It goes on, you know,', 'in this way:--']
qText: It goes on, you know, in this way:--
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['_Twinkle, twinkle, twinkle, twinkle_--']
qText: _Twinkle, twinkle, twinkle, twinkle_--
speaker: The Dormouse
refExp: the Dormouse shook itself and began singing

qTextArr: ["Well, I'd hardly finished the first verse,", "when the\nQueen jumped up and bawled out, 'He's murdering the time! Off with his\nhead!'"]
qText:
Well, I'd hardly finished the first verse, when the
Queen jumped up and bawled out, 'He's murdering the time! Off with his
head!'
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['How dreadfully savage!']
qText: How dreadfully savage!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['And ever since that,', "he won't\ndo a thing I ask! It's always six o'clock now."]
qText:
And ever since that, he won't
do a thing I ask! It's always six o'clock now.
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Is that the reason so many\ntea-things are put out here?']
qText:
Is that the reason so many
tea-things are put out here?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Yes, that's it,", "it's always tea-time,\nand we've no time to wash the things between whiles."]
qText:
Yes, that's it, it's always tea-time,
and we've no time to wash the things between whiles.
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Then you keep moving round, I suppose?']
qText: Then you keep moving round, I suppose?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Exactly so,', 'as the things get used up.']
qText: Exactly so, as the things get used up.
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['But what happens when you come to the beginning again?']
qText: But what happens when you come to the beginning again?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Suppose we change the subject,', "I'm getting tired of this. I vote the young lady tells us a story."]
qText: Suppose we change the subject, I'm getting tired of this. I vote the young lady tells us a story.
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ["I'm afraid I don't know one,"]
qText: I'm afraid I don't know one,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["I wasn't asleep,", 'I heard every word you fellows were saying.']
qText: I wasn't asleep, I heard every word you fellows were saying.
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['Tell us a story!']
qText: Tell us a story!
speaker: Hare

qTextArr: ['Yes, please do!']
qText: Yes, please do!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['And be quick about it,', "or you'll be asleep again\nbefore it's done."]
qText:
And be quick about it, or you'll be asleep again
before it's done.
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Once upon a time there were three little sisters,', 'and their names were Elsie, Lacie, and Tillie; and\nthey lived at the bottom of a well--']
qText:
Once upon a time there were three little sisters, and their names were Elsie, Lacie, and Tillie; and
they lived at the bottom of a well--
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['What did they live on?']
qText: What did they live on?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['They lived on treacle,']
qText: They lived on treacle,
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ["They couldn't have done that, you know,", "they'd have been ill."]
qText: They couldn't have done that, you know, they'd have been ill.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['So they were,', '_very_ ill.']
qText: So they were, _very_ ill.
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['But\nwhy did they live at the bottom of a well?']
qText:
But
why did they live at the bottom of a well?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Take some more tea,']
qText: Take some more tea,
speaker: Hare
refExp: the March Hare said to Alice

qTextArr: ["I've had nothing yet,", "so I can't\ntake more."]
qText:
I've had nothing yet, so I can't
take more.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["You mean you can't take _less_,", "it's very easy to\ntake _more_ than nothing."]
qText:
You mean you can't take _less_, it's very easy to
take _more_ than nothing.
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Nobody asked _your_ opinion,']
qText: Nobody asked _your_ opinion,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Who's making personal remarks now?"]
qText: Who's making personal remarks now?
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['Why did they live at the bottom of a well?']
qText: Why did they live at the bottom of a well?
speaker: Alice
refExp: she helped herself to some tea and breadandbutter and then turned to the Dormouse and repeated

qTextArr: ['It was a treacle-well.']
qText: It was a treacle-well.
speaker: The Dormouse
refExp: The Dormouse again took a minute or two to think about it and then said

qTextArr: ["There's no such thing!"]
qText: There's no such thing!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["If you can't be civil, you'd better finish the story for\nyourself."]
qText:
If you can't be civil, you'd better finish the story for
yourself.
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['No, please go on!', "I won't interrupt again. I\ndare say there may be _one_."]
qText:
No, please go on! I won't interrupt again. I
dare say there may be _one_.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['One, indeed!']
qText: One, indeed!
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['And so these three little sisters--they were learning to draw,\nyou know--']
qText:
And so these three little sisters--they were learning to draw,
you know--
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['What did they draw?']
qText: What did they draw?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Treacle,']
qText: Treacle,
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['I want a clean cup,', "let's all move one place\non."]
qText:
I want a clean cup, let's all move one place
on.
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ["But I don't understand. Where did they draw the treacle\nfrom?"]
qText:
But I don't understand. Where did they draw the treacle
from?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['You can draw water out of a water-well,', 'so I should\nthink you could draw treacle out of a treacle-well--eh, stupid?']
qText:
You can draw water out of a water-well, so I should
think you could draw treacle out of a treacle-well--eh, stupid?
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ['But they were _in_ the well,']
qText: But they were _in_ the well,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Of course they were,', '--well in.']
qText: Of course they were, --well in.
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['They were learning to draw,', 'and they drew all manner of\nthings--everything that begins with an M--']
qText:
They were learning to draw, and they drew all manner of
things--everything that begins with an M--
speaker: The Dormouse

qTextArr: ['Why with an M?']
qText: Why with an M?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['Why not?']
qText: Why not?
speaker: Hare

qTextArr:
['--that begins with an M, such as
mouse-traps, and the moon, and memory, and muchness--you know you say
things are', '--did you ever see such a thing as a
drawing of a muchness?']
qText:
--that begins with an M, such as
mouse-traps, and the moon, and memory, and muchness--you know you say
things are --did you ever see such a thing as a
drawing of a muchness?
speaker: The Dormouse
refExp: it woke up again with a little shriek and went on

qTextArr: ['Really, now you ask me,', "I don't\nthink--"]
qText:
Really, now you ask me, I don't
think--
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Then you shouldn't talk,"]
qText: Then you shouldn't talk,
speaker: The Hatter

qTextArr: ["At any rate I'll never go _there_ again!", "It's the stupidest tea-party I ever was at in\nall my life!"]
qText:
At any rate I'll never go _there_ again! It's the stupidest tea-party I ever was at in
all my life!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["That's very curious!", "But\neverything's curious today. I think I may as well go in at once."]
qText:
That's very curious! But
everything's curious today. I think I may as well go in at once.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Now, I'll manage better this time,"]
qText: Now, I'll manage better this time,
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Look out now, Five! Don't go splashing paint over me\nlike that!"]
qText:
Look out now, Five! Don't go splashing paint over me
like that!
speaker: Two

qTextArr: ["I couldn't help it,", 'Seven jogged my\nelbow.']
qText:
I couldn't help it, Seven jogged my
elbow.
speaker: Five

qTextArr: ["That's right, Five! Always lay the\nblame on others!"]
qText:
That's right, Five! Always lay the
blame on others!
speaker: Seven

qTextArr: ["_You'd_ better not talk!", 'I heard the Queen say only\nyesterday you deserved to be beheaded!']
qText:
_You'd_ better not talk! I heard the Queen say only
yesterday you deserved to be beheaded!
speaker: Five

qTextArr: ['What for?']
qText: What for?
speaker: Two
refExp: said the one who had spoken first

qTextArr: ["That's none of _your_ business, Two!"]
qText: That's none of _your_ business, Two!
speaker: Seven

qTextArr: ['Yes, it _is_ his business!', "and I'll tell him--it was for\nbringing the cook tulip-roots instead of onions."]
qText:
Yes, it _is_ his business! and I'll tell him--it was for
bringing the cook tulip-roots instead of onions.
speaker: Five

qTextArr: ['Well, of all the unjust\nthings--']
qText:
Well, of all the unjust
things--
speaker: Seven
refExp: Seven flung down his brush and had just begun

qTextArr: ['Would you tell me,', 'why you are\npainting those roses?']
qText:
Would you tell me, why you are
painting those roses?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["Why the fact is, you see, Miss, this here ought to have been a
_red_ rose-tree, and we put a white one in by mistake; and if the Queen
was to find it out, we should all have our heads cut off, you know. So
you see, Miss, we're doing our best, afore she comes, to--"]
qText:
Why the fact is, you see, Miss, this here ought to have been a
_red_ rose-tree, and we put a white one in by mistake; and if the Queen
was to find it out, we should all have our heads cut off, you know. So
you see, Miss, we're doing our best, afore she comes, to--

qTextArr: ['The Queen! The Queen!']
qText: The Queen! The Queen!
speaker: Five
refExp: Five who had been anxiously looking across the garden called out

qTextArr: ['and besides, what would be the use of a\nprocession,', "if people had all to lie down upon their\nfaces, so that they couldn't see it?"]
qText:
and besides, what would be the use of a
procession, if people had all to lie down upon their
faces, so that they couldn't see it?
speaker: Alice

qText: Who is this?

Why, they're only a pack of cards, after

How should _I_ know? It's

qText: Nonsense!

Consider, my

Turn
them over!

qText: Get up!

Leave off that! You make me giddy. What _have_ you been doing

addressee: ['The White Rabbit', 'Alice', 'The Knave Of Hearts', 'Seven', 'Two', 'Five', 'The King Of Hearts']

speaker: Two
addressee: ['The White Rabbit', 'Alice', 'The Knave Of Hearts', 'Seven', 'Five', 'The King Of Hearts', 'The Queen']

qTextArr: ["You shan't be beheaded!"]
qText: You shan't be beheaded!

qText: Are their heads off? That's right! Can you play croquet?

qText: Yes!

qText: Come on, then!

qText: It's--it's a very fine day!

qText: Very, --where's the Duchess?
speaker: Alice
addressee: ['The White Rabbit', 'The Knave Of Hearts', 'The King Of Hearts', 'The Queen']

qTextArr: ['Hush! Hush!', "She's under\nsentence of execution."]
qText:
Hush! Hush! She's under
sentence of execution.
speaker: The White Rabbit

qTextArr: ['What for?']
qText: What for?
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["Did you say 'What a pity!'?"]
qText: Did you say 'What a pity!'?
speaker: The White Rabbit

No, I didn't, I don't think it's at all a pity. I said
'What for?'
speaker: Alice

She boxed the Queen's ears-- Oh, hush! The Queen will hear you! You see, she came rather late, and the

qText: Get to your places!

speaker: The Queen

refExp: the Queen was in a furious passion and went stamping about and shouting

and then, what would become of me? They're dreadfully
fond of beheading people here; the great wonder is, that there's any
one left alive!
speaker: Alice

It's the Cheshire Cat: now I shall have somebody to talk
to.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['How are you getting on?']
qText: How are you getting on?
speaker: The Cat

It's no use
speaking to it, till its ears have come, or at least one
of them.
speaker: Alice

qTextArr:
["I don't think they play at all fairly,", "and they all quarrel so dreadfully one can't hear
oneself speak--and they don't seem to have any rules in particular; at
least, if there are, nobody attends to them--and you've no idea how
confusing it is all the things being alive; for instance, there's the
arch I've got to go through next walking about at the other end of the
ground--and I should have croqueted the Queen's hedgehog just now, only
it ran away when it saw mine coming!"]
qText:
I don't think they play at all fairly, and they all quarrel so dreadfully one can't hear
oneself speak--and they don't seem to have any rules in particular; at
least, if there are, nobody attends to them--and you've no idea how
confusing it is all the things being alive; for instance, there's the
arch I've got to go through next walking about at the other end of the
ground--and I should have croqueted the Queen's hedgehog just now, only
it ran away when it saw mine coming!
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ['How do you like the Queen?']
qText: How do you like the Queen?
speaker: The Cat

qTextArr: ['Not at all,', "she's so extremely--"]
qText: Not at all, she's so extremely--
speaker: Alice

qTextArr: ["--likely to win, that it's hardly worth while finishing the game."]
qText: --likely to win, that it's hardly worth while finishing the game.
speaker: Alice

qText: Who _are_ you talking to?

qText: I'd rather not,

qText:
Don't be impertinent, and don't look at me like

qText:
A cat may look at a king, I've read that in some book,

qTextArr: ['Well, it must be removed,']
qText: Well, it must be removed,
speaker: The King Of Hearts

qText:
My dear! I wish you would
have this cat removed!

qTextArr: ['Off with his head!']
qText: Off with his head!
speaker: The Queen
